      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@DarrellTeague Sure, but that’s not caused by different JVMs, it’s caused by using different classes.  In fact, every Swing component’s documentation says:  “<b>Warning:</b> Serialized objects of this class will not be compatible with future Swing releases. The current serialization support is appropriate for short term storage or RMI between applications running the same version of Swing.”  The warning is there because normally, serializable classes in Java SE do in fact take responsibility for serialized compatibility between versions."
