    "body" : "<ol>\n<li><p>From <a href=\"http://www.parashift.com/c++-faq-lite/serialization.html#faq-36.1\" rel=\"noreferrer\">What's this \"serialization\" thing all about?</a>:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>It lets you take an object or group of\n  objects, put them on a disk or send\n  them through a wire or wireless\n  transport mechanism, then later,\n  perhaps on another computer, reverse\n  the process: resurrect the original\n  object(s). The basic mechanisms are to\n  flatten object(s) into a\n  one-dimensional stream of bits, and to\n  turn that stream of bits back into the\n  original object(s).</p>\n  \n  <p>Like the Transporter on Star Trek,\n  it's all about taking something\n  complicated and turning it into a flat\n  sequence of 1s and 0s, then taking\n  that sequence of 1s and 0s (possibly\n  at another place, possibly at another\n  time) and reconstructing the original\n  complicated \"something.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>So, implement the <code>Serializable</code> interface when you need to store a copy of the object, send them to another process which runs on the same system or over the network.</p></li>\n<li><p>Because you want to store or send an object.</p></li>\n<li><p>It makes storing and sending objects easy. It has nothing to do with security.</p></li>\n</ol>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 70373,
      "reputation" : 7842,
      "user_id" : 204143,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 57,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8170ad848a91c4cc534755d37befb6cc?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Steve Emmerson",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/204143/steve-emmerson"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 55,
    "last_activity_date" : 1562750799,
    "last_edit_date" : 1562750799,
    "creation_date" : 1293565110,
    "answer_id" : 4548905,
    "question_id" : 4548816,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<ol>\n<li><p>Implement the <code>Serializable</code> interface when you want to be able to convert an instance of a class into a series of bytes or when you think that a <code>Serializable</code> object might reference an instance of your class.</p></li>\n<li><p><code>Serializable</code> classes are useful when you want to persist instances of them or send them over a wire.</p></li>\n<li><p>Instances of <code>Serializable</code> classes can be easily transmitted. Serialization does have some security consequences, however. Read Joshua Bloch's <strong>Effective Java</strong>.</p></li>\n</ol>\n"
  }, {
